post_text: Tomorrow, on the 19th anniversary of the tragedy that took place on September 11, 2001, our district will honor and remember the victims and the families who lost their loved ones on this day. Please join us for a district-wide moment of silence at 8:46 a.m. This time marks the minute American Airlines Flight 11 struck the North Tower of the World Trade Center.

post_text: We are proud to announce that our superintendent, Dr. Moore, has been asked to serve on a panel of leaders in partnership with the International Center for Leadership in Education. The panel discussion will provide support and guidance to other superintendents on how to effectively lead and establish conditions that ensure successful re-openings of schools for students and staff.

post_text:
To clarify our recent post regarding the designs on masks permitted on campuses, please see the update below. Masks must be aligned with our Student Code of Conduct, Board Policy 5517.01, which protects students and staff from bullying and harassment within our educational environments.
This includes the display or transmission (in any medium,including clothing, jewelry, posters, stickers, flyers or buttons) writings, images or symbols that are reasonably expected to be divisive, demeaning, or offensive to any person or group or disruptive to the learning environment.

post_text:
To clarify our recent post regarding the designs on masks permitted on campuses, please see the update below. Masks must be aligned with our Student Code of Conduct, Board Policy 5517.01, which protects students and staff from bullying and harassment within our educational environments.
This includes the display or transmission (in any medium,including clothing, jewelry, posters, stickers, flyers or buttons) writings, images or symbols that are reasonably expected to be divisive, demeaning, or offensive to any person or group or disruptive to the learning environment.

IMPORTANT: Students are NOT changing their passwords. They are just logging in to see the new password and write it down for their records.
To increase security and comply with our updated digital tools, ALL student passwords have been changed. The student's previous password will continue to work through 5:00 p.m. on 8/14/2020. We've done this so students and families can login to FOCUS and see their new password before their old password expires.

Students can also wait and obtain their new passwords when school starts with teacher assistance (includes school, transitional, and virtual enrollment options).
https://t.co/Gl5zKZblUV

post_text: All warnings and watches have been discontinued for our area, and shelters have been demobilized. Thank you to our staff who served in shelters for your hard work and dedication to our community. We are looking forward to welcoming back our teachers and staff tomorrow, Monday, August 3rd!
shared_text:
Indian River County Emergency Services Department
August 2 at 11:08 AM ·

The Storm Surge Watch has been discontinued for our area. A tropical storm warning remains in effect from Jupiter Inlet north to Surf City North Carolina.
Strong tropical storm conditions are still likely along the coast (especially barrier islands). The latest forecast moves Isaias northward near to just along the immediate coast of east central Florida into tonight.

At any time today/tonight, rainbands may temporarily come onshore. If this occurs, sustained winds of 50-50 mph, with damaging gusts up to 70 mph will likely occur in the areas affected by these rainbands.

Moderate to locally major beach erosion is expected. Seas will remain dangerous, and the rip current hazard will remain high to extreme into next week.

Isaias is no longer forecast to regain hurricane strength. Winds gusts from 45-65 mph are forecast for our area, with gusts to 75 mph possible. Periods of heavy rain.

• Hurricane Warnings have been downgraded to a Tropical Storm Warning.
• The latest forecast moves Isaias northward near to just along our coast today.
• Isaias is no longer forecast to regain hurricane strength.
• Wind gusts from 45-65 are forecast for our area with gusts to 75 mph possible.
• Squalls will continue to move onshore and there will be periods of heavy rain.

Indian River County
July 31 at 7:04 PM ·

Due to the anticipated impacts of Hurricane Isaias, City of Vero Beach and Indian River County Beach Access Points will close to the public tomorrow, August 1st, at 5:00pm.

Dependent on local weather conditions, the affected Beach Access Points are tentatively scheduled to re-open on the morning of Monday, August 3rd.

For up to date information on Indian River County’s response to Hurricane Isaias, sign up to receive emergency alerts from the Indian River County Emergency Services Department by visiting www.irces.com.

shared_text:
Moonshot Moment: 90% Literacy by Third Grade
July 30 at 10:31 AM ·

Fun summer activity - Recreate our Moonshot Moment Rocket and post pictures using the hashtag #MoonshotMomentRocket.

The Moonshot rocket is our symbol of ensuring a better future for everyone, by having children ready for kindergarten and reading on grade level by the end of third grade.

Show your support for our Moonshot goal by posting a picture of your logo creation. Chalk art! Crayon! Sculpture! Surprise us with your creativity and enjoy the rest of summer!
Prizes will be sent to the post with the most “likes” by the end of August, and to the most unique.

post_text:
The deadline to complete the Instructional Model Options Form has been extended to Wednesday, July 15th at 5 p.m. Please log in to your parent portal account in FOCUS, select Forms, and complete the “Fall 2020 Instructional Model Options Form” to make the final selection for your student’s instructional model for the reopening of schools in August. One selection form must be completed for each student in your family. If you do not know or have your student's ID number or do not see them in the drop down menu on the form, please contact your student's school.
To access the instructional model form, register for a FOCUS parent portal account, helpline information, and more, click below:

https://www.indianriverschools.org/news/coronavirus_information_and_updates/school_reopening

post_text:
Seniors and families, the schedule for the day of each graduation (VBHS JULY 10) (SRHS JULY 11) is as follows:

9 a.m. ceremony: LIVESTREAMED. Seniors only. Full graduation with speeches, recognitions, and WALKING as a senior class. Families can tune in on YouTube at home to watch live.

5 p.m. drive-thru: LIVESTREAMED. Seniors and families (1 vehicle per senior) are invited back for a drive-thru graduation, where names will be called and seniors will have the opportunity to walk again with family members present.

Seniors may choose to attend one or both ceremonies. Families are invited to attend in vehicle with their graduate at 5 p.m. Both ceremonies will be available LIVE and for future viewing on our YouTube channel.

post_text: This morning, Dr. Moore interviewed with Jon Shainman WPTV5 about what the future of the SDIRC looks like, and how we are envisioning reopening in the fall and adhering to CDC guidlines. post_text: Congratulations to our next winner! It is Teacher Appreciation Week & we are celebrating our SDIRC teachers! Each day we post a new question or theme. Post your response to Facebook and Twitter then email it to socialmedia@indianriverschools.org to nominate that teacher for a chance to win a Publix gift card from our partners at the United Way.

post_text: Join us today at 10:30 a.m. for our SDIRC 2020 Outstanding Volunteer of the Year Virtual Ceremony! The ceremony will be livestreamed on Facebook and YouTube and will be available for viewing after the session. Thank you to all of our SDIRC volunteers who give freely of their time and talent, your efforts are greatly making a difference in our schools!
